Finally, the OCPs concentrations in three real water samples, which were collected from lake water (1#, 2#) and tap water (3#), and three fruit juice samples (cranberry juice, grape juice, and peach juice) were analyzed by the proposed method. Analysis results implied that PPC, g-CHD, and a-CHD were detected in lake water samples with concentration ranging from 0.61–5.3 ng/L, none of OCPs was found in tap water sample (Table 3
                        ). The recoveries for water samples with spiked OCPs concentration of 0.5 ng/L were in the range of 80.1 %−105.2 %. For the analysis of OCPs from fruit juice samples (Table 4
                        ), HCB, g-CHD, a-CHD, and CBZ were found in cranberry juice samples at concentrations of 7.5–28.1 ng/L. TFR and HCB were detected in grape juice with concentrations of 8.1 and 6.9 ng/L, respectively. The OCPs were not found in peach juice. The recoveries were observed in the range of 71 %−106.8 % with spiked OCPs concentration of 10 ng/L for cranberry juice and grape juice, and 0.5 ng/L for peach juice. Satisfactory recoveries and RSDs further validated the practical applicability of proposed method for analysis of OCPs from real water and fruit juice samples.
